# Phase 8F — Image Tagging, Test Runner, and Merge Checklist

This phase documents the workflow that makes the PXE content image easier to test before merge and easier to consume after merge.

The goal is simple:

```text
Use :test when validating a branch or merge request.
Use :latest after the change is merged and promoted.
Keep sha-* tags for traceability.
```

## Why this matters

Before the test runner was added, testing required copying scripts to the VM or cloning the project where the container was running.

Now the image carries its own test scripts. That means a user can pull the image and run a single command to validate the image contents, generator behavior, override behavior, validation policy, and generated HTTP content.

## Recommended image tags

The pipeline should publish tags that make both testing and traceability easy.

Recommended behavior:

| Pipeline type | Recommended tags | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Branch or merge request validation | `test`, `sha-<short-sha>` | Easy testing plus exact build traceability |
| Merge request pipeline, if MR variables are available | `test`, `mr-<iid>`, `test-<short-sha>`, `sha-<short-sha>` | Easy testing plus MR-specific traceability |
| Default branch after merge | `latest`, `main-<short-sha>`, `sha-<short-sha>` | Promoted image for normal use |
| Git tag pipeline | `<git-tag>`, `latest`, `sha-<short-sha>` | Release-style tagging |

The most important tags are:

```text
test
latest
sha-<short-sha>
```

`test` is intentionally a moving tag. It is meant for quick manual validation of the latest image produced by the active branch or merge request.

`sha-<short-sha>` is the exact immutable-ish build reference for troubleshooting.

`latest` should represent the promoted image from the default branch after merge.

## Recommended test command

Run all built-in tests against the `:test` image:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

A successful run should show these test groups passing:

```text
Basic image test passed
Overrides and preserve policy test passed
Validation / health policy test passed
```

