Use `all` before merge.

Use a single group when troubleshooting a specific failure.

## Test runner files

Source files in the repo:

```text
tests/
  pxe-content-test
  test-basic-image.sh
  test-overrides-and-preserve-policy.sh
  test-validation-health-policy.sh
  test-lib.sh
```

Installed paths inside the image:

```text
/usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test
/usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/
```

The Dockerfile should copy the test directory into the image, make the scripts executable, and create the `/usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test` symlink.

## Test runner requirements

The image must include:

```text
python3
nginx
bash
```

The test scripts must have:

```text
Unix line endings
executable permissions
```

A good quick verification command is:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /bin/sh \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  -lc 'head -1 /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test | cat -A; command -v bash; ls -l /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test'
```

Good output should include:

```text
#!/usr/bin/env bash$
/usr/bin/bash
```

or another valid Bash path.

If the first line shows `^M`, the script has Windows line endings and the image needs to be rebuilt after fixing them.

## What the passing tests prove

Passing tests prove the image can:

- run the generator
- compile the generator script
- detect valid fake RHEL ISO trees
- ignore incomplete fake ISO trees
- generate `boot.ipxe`
- generate Kickstarts
- generate `index.html`
- generate `status.json`
- generate `status.txt`
- generate `isos.txt`
- serve generated content over HTTP
- render Jinja templates and partials
- use override profiles
- use override templates
- preserve manual `/ks` edits when policy is `preserve`
- overwrite manual `/ks` edits when policy is `overwrite`
- report validation issues in `warn` mode
- fail on validation issues in `fail` mode
- avoid leaking the root password hash into status and index files

## What the tests do not prove

The tests do not prove:

- DHCP is configured correctly
- a physical machine can PXE boot on the real network
- a VM can boot through the real PXE flow
- a real RHEL install completes against a real ISO tree
- Foreman integration works
- Ansible post-install automation works

Those are higher-level integration tests.

Do not block normal documentation or generator cleanup changes on a full real PXE install unless the change affects actual boot or install behavior.

## Recommended merge workflow

Use this process for normal changes:

1. Push the branch.
2. Confirm the pipeline builds and pushes the `:test` image.
3. Run the built-in test command:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

4. Confirm all three test groups pass.
5. Review the changed docs, templates, scripts, and Dockerfile.
6. Merge the MR.
7. Confirm the default branch pipeline publishes `:latest`.

## When to run a real PXE boot test

Run a real VM or hardware PXE test when changing:

- generated kernel arguments
- `boot.ipxe` boot target logic
- Kickstart storage logic
- Kickstart repo logic
- firmware behavior for UEFI or BIOS
- RHEL version-specific boot behavior
- Nginx serving paths used by real clients

For documentation-only changes, test-script updates, or minor status/index changes, the built-in image test is usually enough.

## Common failures

### `No such file or directory` when running `pxe-content-test`

Usually caused by one of these:

- `/usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test` is missing
- the symlink points to a missing file
- Bash is missing
- the script has Windows line endings

Check with:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /bin/sh \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  -lc 'ls -l /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/; head -1 /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test | cat -A; command -v bash || true'
```

### Permission denied during temporary Nginx test

The basic test creates temporary content under `/tmp`.

The test script should ensure the temporary test tree is readable and executable:

```bash
chmod -R a+rX "${TEST_ROOT}"
```

The temporary Nginx test config should run as root inside the test container:

```nginx
user root;
```

### Jinja partial is undefined

Use quoted include paths:

```jinja
{% include "partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2" %}
```

or:

```jinja
{% include 'partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2' %}
```

Do not use unquoted include paths:

```jinja
{% include partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2 %}
```

### Test image did not update

Check the pipeline image destinations.

For easy testing, branch or MR pipelines should publish:

```text
:test
```

If the pipeline publishes only `test-<branch-name>`, either run that specific tag or update the CI tag logic to also push `test`.

